#johdteam time for @nilo_pedrazzini üéôÔ∏è"I'm Editorial Assistant and Copyeditor for JOHD, and DPhil student in Linguistics at @UniofOxford. I work on computational linguistics and formal semantics for ancient languages and I'm into humanities, data science and their intersections." https://t.co/5aSoovOJMK

Where? #JOHD is specifically dedicated to #datapapers for the #Humanities. We publish short data papers, 1000-word descriptions of a dataset or resource, and full-length research papers, 3000-5000 words about methods and challenges in the creation or analysis of datasets 9/9
How to publish my data? One way is to publish a #datapaper: a publication that describes an #openaccess dataset or resource, stored in a repository and that can be used by other researchers. 8/9

It doesn't mean giving away your work: it gives you further recognition, both through citation (required by almost all #opendatalicenses) and measurable metrics of impact. It increases visibility, data can be consulted and (must be) cited.
#transparency #datadocumentation 7/9

Summing up: why publishing about my #data and #metadata, and why in #openaccess? Because it improves reach, dissemination, sustainability, research value, standards development, student engagement, development of new projects, and enables future work. #freereuse #openlicence 6/9

The Epigraphic Database Heidelberg #EDH, a project to publish in digital form the inscriptions of the Roman Empire. #Openlicensed, #OpenData in standard formats, by Frank Grieshaber‚û°Ô∏èhttps://t.co/MkufHeXy57
About the Open Epigraphic Data Unconference https://t.co/n0xDTVarvd 5/9

#Datapaper published by #JOHD at https://t.co/SS1YiKOqa7.
Applications: #linguistics, stylistics, authorship attribution, teaching. 4/9

The Diorisis Ancient Greek Corpus: a digital collection of ancient Greek texts used for a computational model of #semanticchange in ancient Greek (@BarbaraMcGilli & Alessandro Vatri). It can be applied to other research questions about ancient Greek #reusable #linguistics 3/9

#JOHD encourages researchers to make their #digitalresearchdata freely accessible and openly licensed for reuse. Why? Publishing your data and describing it makes it more visible and therefore more likely to be reused and preserved. #openaccess

9/10

One of JOHD‚Äôs #copyeditors will work on the revised version of your paper and will send you back the document with their feedback and comments. This is your last chance to make edits to the text!
8/10

After the #peerreview, you can upload the revised version via your #JOHD portal. The editor will provide a final decision on the publication of your paper
7/10

Provide a #coverletter with: the corresponding author's contact details; the context of your submission and why it is appropriate for #JOHD; 3 scholars to review your paper. If you need a discount or waiver for the publication fee (APC), mention it and you will be contacted. 6/10

Add the #DOI provided by the #repository you chose under the ‚Äúrepository location‚Äù section in the #datapaper. 
4/10

https://t.co/5DkHYLIRIg.
